John Edward: Language skills essential for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools maintain a track record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with a further series of outstanding examination results, which have been strengthened by the success of individuals and all peoples together in sport, art, music and other community endeavours.
With over 30, 000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector where we can design and implement a customised school curriculum, we are seeing the rise of modern languages as a desirable subject choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, that goes to his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, that goes to his heart."
That is a strong reminder that we cannot rely on English if we want to build relationships with and trust people from other countries.
From the most recent examination results this year, we find that languages are top of the league tables with the highest pass rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved an A grade of Honours.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS membership schools, showed that 72 percent of students achieved Grade A Honours in Mandarin, and 72 percent who studied German, 69 percent who studied French and 63 percent who studied Spanish also achieved Grade A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now viewed as a choice of subject, as are STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) subjects in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
A survey carried out by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 found that for employers' reasons for having difficulty filling vacancies, 17 per cent were due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore language skills are increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more potential job opportunities requiring languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the profession one would choose, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future that they have a lifelong skill similar to this one.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically promote a multilingual person to the competition.
According to YouGov's survey of more than 4, 000 UK adults in 2013, 75 percent of them could not speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation and the only language that a two-digit percentage of them spoke was French, 15 percent.
That is why it is important for children today to invest in language teaching.
If children have more than one language, especially those in developing economies, they will be more likely to find meaningful employment.
Different languages will be taught in each school within Scotland.
Some schools will focus on contemporary and classical languages, while other schools will teach the languages that are considered to be the most important languages for the UK looking forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from within independent schools, with specialist teaching staff in this area.
Scotland's independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills to succeed, whatever happens in the future.
It is undeniable at this time that, in a global business environment, languages remain vital to the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
In fact, languages should actually be viewed as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this option, diversity and excellence to the young people of Scotland.
I need to be well looked after.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
