North Korea says that there is no ‘no chance' that they will unilaterally disarm because of lack of confidence.
North Korea's Foreign Minister told the United Nations on Saturday that ongoing sanctions were aggravating their lack of confidence in the United States and that there was no way the country would give up its nuclear weapons, unilaterally, in these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the UN General Assembly that North Korea had shown "very good will" during the past year, insofar as it halted nuclear tests and missile tests, built the nuclear test site consecutively and pledged not to increase nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"We don't have the same response from the United States," he said.
"Without any trust in the United States, our national security will not be trusted and in these circumstances, there is no way that we will unilaterally disarm, first and foremost."
While Ri again made popular complaints to North Korea regarding the United States, which opposed a "progressive" approach to nuclear disarmament, in which North Korea would be given a concession, as it took small steps, her statement seemed important in that it did not reject a net of unilateral nuclear disarmament as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri made reference to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the US President, still in office, and the leader of North Korea in Singapore on June 12, when Kim promised to work "to achieve nuclear disarmament in the Korean peninsula" while Trump made a promise about North Korea's security.
North Korea wants an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must surrender its nuclear weapons in advance.
Washington has also resisted requests to ease severe international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists that "nuclear disarmament will be done first and foremost" and increases the pressure with sanctions to achieve their aim in a coercive manner, and even opposes "notice of the war being over", Ri said.
"The idea that sanctions can overwhelm us is an idea from people who are ignorant about us.
But the problem is that sanctions, which are continuing, are contributing to our lack of confidence.
Ri made no reference to another summit being between Kim and Trump, mentioned by the American leader at the United Nations earlier in the week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months and added: "If South Korea rather than the United States were the party involved in this issue of nuclear disarmament, the nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula would not be thrust in this way."
However, the way in which Ri spoke in his speech was very different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korea's rockets would be directed to the US mainland after Trump, "Mr. Evil President", "rocket man" on a suicide mission to call Kim.
This year, at the United Nations, Trump praised Kim for his courage in taking steps to disarm, even though he threatened last year to "totally destroy" North Korea.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn't mean a certain time for disarmament, saying, "if it takes two years, three years or five years - it doesn't matter."
China and Russia claim that the United Nations Security Council should compensate Pyongyang for the steps taken.
But Mike Pompeo, U.S. Secretary of State with the United Nations Security Council said on Thursday that: "Security Council sanctions must be applied robustly and without any failure until full nuclear disarmament is achieved and certified."
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions on North Korea since 2006 to halt funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the margins of the UN General Assembly and said afterwards that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for the second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit didn't go too well.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying progress had been made; but North Korea criticized him within a few hours because he had "made claims about how to cheat."
North Korea promised in a meeting with Moon this month that it would destroy a missile site, if the United States took "corresponding measures."
He said Kim told him that his "corresponding measures" were security promises that Trump had made in Singapore and taking steps to achieve normal relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course to get enough rest.
A new course has started at Harvard University this year to increase sleep for all undergraduates to counteract the growing culture of what is being studied' through the night with the aid of caffeine."
A student discovered that students at the university, which is in the first place in the world, have no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, put the course together, believing it to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk on the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
‘At the end of the lecture, a girl came up to me and said: ‘Why haven’t I been told this already, in my senior year?’
"She said no one had told her before about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told the Telegraph.
The course, which was offered for the first time this year, explains to students the key points about good sleep habits and how they contribute to academic and athletic performance, as well as improving general well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's medical services, said the university took a decision to introduce the course, when he found that students were very lack of sleep during the week.
A series of interactive tasks are part of the hour-long course.
In one section, there is an image of a dormitory, where students knock on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes and books to respond to the effects of caffeine and light and how sleep deprivation affects athletic functioning and the importance of a routine at bedtime.
In another section, participants are told how long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
Then a map of the campus with interactive icons, urges the participants to reflect on their daily routine.
‘We know that it will not change student behaviour immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know - how you would have the right to know about the health effects of smoking," said Professor Czeisler.
There is still a culture of pride in ‘staying awake during the night’, he said. According to him, modern technology and the pressure on students, which is constantly increasing, means that lack of sleep is an increasing problem.
A student should ensure that he/she has sufficient sleep of good quality as a ‘secret tool', he/she said, to avoid stress, fatigue and anxiety, even to avoid weight gain, as lack of sleep puts the brain in hunger mode, as he/she is regularly hungry.
Raymond So, 19, from California, who is studying chemistry and biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having done one of his classes during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course opened his eyes and urged him to look for a course for the whole campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all undergraduates to do a similar program of study, before entering the competitive institution.
