The person who devised the World Wide Web has plans to launch a New Internet to challenge Google and Facebook.
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is set to start a new initiative, which will compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project from the famous technologist, Inrupt, is a company that builds on Berners-Lee's open source platform, Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where they will store their data, and who is allowed to access that information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee stated, with humor, that the desire behind Inrupt is a "global domination."
"We have to do it now," he said of the initiative.
"It's a historic moment."
The app uses Solid technology to allow people to "create their personal, online data warehouse" or create a POD.
It can contain contact details, lists of things to do, a calendar, a music library and other personal and professional tools.
It's as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available on a single browser and all are available at the same time.
The unique feature of the online personal data warehouse is that it is solely a user's responsibility to give access to a person, who needs a specific type of information.
The company offers :"personal empowerment through data." on it.
the idea for Inrupt, according to Chief Executive, John Bruce, is to provide appropriate resources, processes and skills so that Solid is available to everyone.
Currently the company consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several developers on the team, who have a contract to work on the project and a community of volunteer coders.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world could create their decentralised apps using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team weren't talking to "Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce a complete change where the business models they have are turned upside down overnight.
"We're not looking for permission."
In a posting on Medium, published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that "Inrupt's mission was to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem, to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network, which is built on Solid.
In 1994, Berners-Lee founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
Over the past several months, a voice, influential in the debate about internet neutrality, has been in Berners-Lee.
Even when launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the Founder and Director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Institute for Open Data.
"I'm very optimistic about the next era of the internet," Berners-Lee said.
Bernard Vann: Celebrates a clerk who won the Victoria Cross in World War 1.
His hometown has been celebrated as a clerk in the Church of England, the only clerk to win the Victoria Cross during World War 1 as a fighter.
The award was won by Lieutenant Colonel, Reverend Bernard Vann, on 29 September 1918 in the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
But he was killed by a sniper four days later and never knew that he had won the highest award in the British army.
His two grandsons unveiled a memorial stone at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire on Saturday.
One of his grandsons, Michael Vann said it was a "wonderful symbolism" that the stone would be unveiled exactly 100 years since his grandfather won the award.
According to the London Gazette of 28 September 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion across the Canal de Saint-Quentin "through heavy fog and under heavy attack from field guns and machine guns."
He later speeded up to the shooters' line and with "excellent courage" guided the line forward before raiding a field gun alone and knocking out three of the detachment.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by German snipers on 4 October 1918 - a month before the end of World War I.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather's actions were "something I could never have done but something that goes to my heart in me."
He and his brother, Doctor James Vann laid a wreath after the parade, which was led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said that he "felt it was a great honour to take part in the parade" and also said that the support that many people will give was showing courage that showed real heroism.
