Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt ‘desperate' as a result of his sexuality.
Olympic diver Tom Daley says he felt he wasn't as good as others when he was growing up because of his sexuality - but that encouraged him to make progress.
The 24-year-old says he didn't realize until he went to secondary school that "everyone wasn't like me."
Speaking on the first Desert Island Discs on Radio 4, which was presented by Lauren Laverne, he said he had talked about the rights of gays to give "hope" to others.
He also said that if he had been a parent now it was not so important for him to win in the Olympics.
The show's regular presenter, Kirsty Young, has taken several months off due to illness.
While on Laverne's first program as a person on a deserted island, Daley stated that he viewed himself as "less human" than everyone else, when he was growing up as "not socially accepted as one would like boys and girls."
He said: "To this day, it's those feelings that make me look at myself as someone who was smaller and felt different, those are the definite things that have given me the power and the strength to be able to achieve things."
He wanted to prove that it was worth ‘something', he said, so as not to disappoint everyone, when they would finally find out about his sexuality.
The two-time Olympic bronze medallist has become a pro-LGBT (Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Transgender) campaigner. He has used his presence at the British Commonwealth Games in Australia this year to call on more countries to decriminalise homosexuality.
He said he spoke out because he felt fortunate to be able to live openly without any implication and wanted to give "hope" to others.
Daley, who was a three-time world champion, said he was "shocked" when he fell in love with American man-made filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013.
Daley married the Oscar winner, who is 20 years older than him last year but said there was never a problem when it comes to the gap between the ages.
"When you suffer so much at a very young age" - he first went to the Olympics, when he was 14 years old and his father died of cancer three years later - he said it was hard to find one of his peers who had so much above in his life.
The couple have been parents since June. They have a son named Robert Ray Black-Daley and Daley said that "the whole outlook on life" had changed.
"If you ask me last year what was important, it was all about ‘winning a gold medal'," he said.
"Do you know, things are more important than Olympic gold medals.
Robbie is my Olympic gold medalist."
His son has the same name as his father, Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40, when he was found to have brain cancer.
Daley said that his father did not accept that he was going to die and one of the last things he asked was if they had their tickets to the London Olympics in 2012 - because he wanted to be in the starting row.
“I couldn’t tell him ‘you won’t be around to be in the first series, Dad,’” he said.
"I had a hand hold on him when he stopped breathing and I didn't admit it was not conclusive until he stopped breathing and he was dead," he said.
The following year, Daley participated in the 2012 Olympics and won a bronze medal.
"I knew that was my dream all my life - diving in front of a home crowd at the Olympics, there couldn't be a better feeling," he said.
He also inspired his first choice of song - Proud by Heather Small - which impressed him in the preparations for the Olympics and still gets him excited.
Desert Island Discs is on BBC Radio 4 every Sunday at 11.15 BST.
