The German warship is again postponed.
The German Navy's newest frigate should have been commissioned in 2014 to replace the Cold War warships, but it won't happen until next year, due to a faulty system and the increasing cost, local media reported.
The commissioning of the "Rhineland-Pfalz," the lead ship of the new frigates of Baden-Wuerttemberg has been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, mentioned by a military spokesman.
The ship should have been part of the Navy in 2014, but there were major post-delivery problems that seriously hampered the ambitious project.
Four Baden-Wuerttemberg ships, ordered by the Navy in 2007, will replace the aging Bremen frigates.
It has been suggested that they will contain a powerful cannon, a combination of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as telecommunications technology such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features are longer maintenance periods - it may be possible to deploy the newest frigates for two years away from home ports.
But, because there was an ongoing delay, it means that the pioneering warships - who would have the opportunity to demonstrate power overseas - will be out of date by the time they are ready, says Die Zeit.
The frigate was unlucky in the news last year, when the German Navy, officially refused to commission the vessel and sent it back to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy sent a ship back to the builder after accepting it.
Not much was known about the reasons for the ship's return, but German media quoted some "failures on software and hardware" if it was not deployed on a combat mission.
Deficiencies in the software were particularly important because the Baden-Wuerttemberg type vessels will be operated by a team of 120 sailors - half of the team was on older Bremen type frigates.
Also, it has come to light that the ship is far too heavy, that this reduces the ship's performance and limits the Navy's ability to upgrade in the future.
The "Rheinland-Pfalz", which weighs 7,000 tons, is believed to be twice as heavy as similar ships used by Germany in World War II.
With the exception of faulty hardware, the cost of the entire project - including the cost of training the staff - is becoming disputed.
The cost is said to have increased to €3.1 billion ($3.6) - up from €2.2 billion at the start.
Problems with the newer frigate are very important due to the recent warnings that the power of the German fleet is diminishing.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, the head of the German parliament's defence committee, admitted that the Navy was "running out of ships that can be evacuated."
The official said the issue had increased over the years because old ships were decommissioned but not replaced with new ships.
He complained that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-type frigates were able to form part of the Navy.
The National Trust is rehearsing the secret life of bats.
New research is underway on an estate in the Scottish Highlands and aims to find out how the batsmen use the countryside to hunt for food.
The results are expected to shed new light on the behavior of the unique flying mammal and help guide conservation activities in the future.
The study of scientists at the Scottish National Trust will follow common bats and soprano pipistrelles, as well as Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at special sites around the estate to follow the batsmen's activities during the season.
The National Health Service (NHS) team will carry out mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
Audio analysis of each record, conducted by experts, will find out the frequency of calls made by bats and what each particular species does.
A habitat map will be made and then a report to show a record of their behaviour in a large picture of the landscape.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation consultant for the Scottish National Trust, hopes that the results will reveal the most important habitat areas for bats and the way in which each of the species uses them.
This information will help demonstrate the benefits of habitat management such as the creation of meadows and how best to conserve woodland for bats and other related species.
The number of bats in Scotland and across the UK has declined dramatically in the last century.
They are threatened by buildings and development work that disrupts their crops and the habitats that are lost.
Wind turbines and lightning can be dangerous where there are fly-paper and some chemical treatments on building materials, as well as attacks by pet cats.
There are no blinds, really.
Their hunting habits at night, however, make their ears more useful than their eyes, when they have to catch prey material.
They detect insects and obstructions in their flight paths from echoes, a sophisticated technique.
The National Trust for Scotland, which is responsible for looking after over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has trained ten experts, who regularly carry out surveys, inspect fences and, sometimes, rescue.
The organisation has established a separate sanctuary for bats, the first and only in Scotland, at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway. It is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The estate's manager, David Thompson, says the estate is the best district for them.
"We have an amazing area for bats here at Threave" he said.
"We have a lot of old buildings, a lot of old trees and a good habitat.
But there's a lot about bats that we don't know yet, so the work we do here and at other estates will help us understand what they need to succeed."
He stresses the importance of checking for bats, prior to the maintenance of buildings and residences, because if destroyed with maternity only, it could kill up to 400 female bats, young bats and possibly all the bats in that area.
Bats are protected and it is against the law to kill, disturb, disturb or destroy their prey.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, asks the public for help.
She said: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and, for many of the species we have, we don't know how the entire communities of them are doing.
