Brexit: The UK would be ‘forever sorry' if it lost car makers.
The UK would be 'forever sorry' if it lost its status as a world leader in car manufacturing post-Brexit, according to Greg Clark, Business Secretary.
He said it was a "concern" that Toyota UK had told the BBC that if Britain left the EEC without a deal, it would stop car production at its factory at Burnaston, near Derby.
"We need a solution," said Mr. Clark.
The Japanese carmaker said jobs could be lost, if there were a delay at the border, in the event that there would not be a solution under Brexit.
The Burnaston factory - which produces the Toyota Auris and Avensis - produced almost 150,000 cars last year and exported 90% of them to the rest of the European Union.
"In my opinion, if Britain leaves the European Union without a deal at the end of March, car production at our factory will stop," said Marvin Cooke, managing director of Toyota at Burnaston.
Other carmakers have said they are concerned about an unresolved EU exit as to how the cross-border trade will work; among them are Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover.
BMW, for example, says it will close the Mini factory in Oxford for a month after Brexit.
The main concerns of car manufacturers are the risks associated with the supply chains in the event of an unresolved Brexit.
Toyota's production line operates on a "just in time" basis. Parts come from suppliers in the UK and EU every 37 minutes for an order-made car.
If the UK leaves without a deal on 29 March, the border could be disrupted, resulting in delays and a shortage of parts, the industry says.
It would not be possible for Toyota to maintain more than a day's inventory at a Derbyshire factory, the company said, and so production would be halted.
Mr Clark said that Theresa May's Chequers plan is "made out accurately to avoid delays like this at the border."
“We need a solution, we want the best solution, not only to allow our current success to continue, but to seize this opportunity,” he told the BBC.
"Our evidence from Toyota and other manufacturers is that we need to be able to continue with the supply chains, which are very successful at the moment."
Toyota was unable to say how long production would be in full stop, but in the long term, it said that additional costs would reduce the factory's competitiveness and eventually lead to job losses.
Peter Tsouvallaris, who has been working at Burnaston for 24 years and is the assemblyman for Unite trade union at the factory, said that his members' concerns were increasing more. "In my experience when these jobs disappear, they never come back.
A government spokesman said: "We have provided a plan, which is accurate and reliable for the future relationship with the EU."
